Black coaches in the country are calling for an opportunity to show their worth. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Black rugby coaches in South Africa are calling for an opportunity to show their worth. Currently, no Super Rugby franchise or Currie Cup team has a black coach at the helm. Black coaches feel they have what it takes to be in charge but aren't being given a chance. READ: Franco Smith appointed interim Italy rugby head coach There are success stories that support this call for recognition. The hope is now for former World Cup-winning Springbok coach Rassie Erasmus to prioritize the elevation of black coaches to leading Super Rugby and Currie Cup teams when he focusses on his position as Director of Rugby at SA Rugby.